column169: RESPONDER RECEIVED NOTIFICATION OF HAZMAT SPILL AT PENN 4 SPLIT 0530AM PST. HAZMAT RESPONDEDER DAWNED APPROPRIATE GEAR AND RESPONDED. INSPECTION OF THE PACKAGE REVEALED HAZMAT SHIPPING PAPERS WITH CORROSIVE DESIGNATION. PACKAGE OBSERVED WET ON TOP AND BOTTOM OF PACKAGING BOX. HAZMAT NOT SEEPING OUT OF SHIPPING CONTAINER. REMOVED HAZMAT FROM AREA NO SPILLAGE SEEN IN AREA. TRANSPORTED TO DMP FOR PROCESSING. OPENED PACKAGE AND OBSERVED CRACKED LID ON A 1 GALLON JUG. TESTED SOLUTION WITH A PH OF 11 PER COLOR CODED CHART. NEUTRALIZED HAZMAT USING SODIUM BICARBONATE IN ITS OWN PLASTIC CONTAINER. RETESTED SOLUTION 2 TIMES TO VERIFY A PH OF 6. USED A SPILL TRAY LINED WITH PLASTIC BAG AND ZEB ZORBENT AND WOODEN MIXING STICK TO SOLIDIFY SOLUTION. ONCE SOLIDIFIED PUT INITIAL PLASTIC BAG WITH SOLIDIFIED SOLUTION, GLOVES, STIRRING STICK, CARDBOARD PACKAGING, GLOVESS, AND PLASTIC JUG IN GREEN HAZMAT BAG. GOOSE NECKED BAG TAPED AND BEGAN HAZMAT PROCESSING.

XPO Logistics contacted ERTS regarding a two metal totes containing hazardous product, Unisol Liquid Red BK 50. A contractor dispatched and observed an estimated 0.5-gallon release from two metal totes that impacted 1’x1’ areas on tops and sides of the totes, the wooden trailer floor, and the concrete dock floor. One of the totes had a loose bung cap that was mis-threaded, and the other tote had a loose lid that was easily tightened. The contractor used simple green to clean-up the release and performed slosh tests on the totes. One 55-gallon DM of waste was generated containing impacted rags, floor debris, and PPE. The totes will ship onto the consignee. XPO will manage all waste created from the response. No storm-drains, waterways, or soil were involved in this incident.

XPO Logistics terminal XWK experienced an over the road release of UN2693 VOxOUT 70C from a 275-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 60-gallons of product released to a 20’ x 3’ area of the trailer floor and a 30’ x 3’ area of the asphalt road below. The tote was damaged due to not being strapped down which caused it to load shift into the trailer wall. The material left in the damaged tote was transferred into a new one for shipment on. The impacted areas were then cleaned with absorbents and degreaser. All the impacted snow, absorbents, and debris were containerized into (3) 55-gallon metal drums. The damaged tote was cut up and placed into a cubic yard box. The waste was removed from the site for disposal.
attachment Name:Hazmat- Damaged Haz Mat Package Disposition 04302024.pdf
attachment Name:Hazmat- Damaged Haz Mat Package Disposition 04302024.pdf
attachment Name:Hazmat- Damaged Haz Mat Package Disposition 04302024.pdf

Clean Harbors was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 56ft-by-6ft area of the trailer floor and the dock floor and estimated that seventy-five (75) gallons of material was released due to a forklift puncturing one (1) 55-gallon metal drum of Hi-Temp 1200 causing it to knock over into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum of PBTCA damaging it. Before Clean Harbors’ arrival, Dayton Freight personnel had placed both damaged drums into two (2) 85-gallon overpacks. Clean Harbors personnel deployed the neutralizer sodium bicarbonate and granular absorbents to the impacted area. They used a pH strip to test the paint inside the metal drum which resulted in a neutral result. All impacted absorbents were placed into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite at the terminal prior to contractor demobilization. After departing off site, Clean Harbors personnel were asked to return to assist with the transfer of the contents of one (1) 85-gallon metal overpack drum to a one (1) 85-gallon poly drum due to the corrosive nature of the contained material. One (1) 85-gallon ploy drum was used to contain neutralizers and granular absorbents utilized during the transfer. Clean Harbors personnel staged one (1) 55-gallon poly drum, one (1) 85-gallon metal drum, and three (3) 85-gallon poly drums onsite at the terminal prior to the contractor demobilization. The generated waste will remain onsite for Dayton Freight’s contracted hazardous waste vendor to coordinate disposal.

column169: On 1/13/2025 at approximately 1030, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 261690 at the ramp facility in Anchorage, reporting undeclared dangerous goods.  The shipment consisted of one fiberboard box, containing 10 inner boxes, and each of those contained 10 plastic bags containing safety matches.  The shipment was flagged and opened by the Customs division.  The Commercial Invoice identified the inner contents as "arithmetical bar"; however, Customs discovered a contradicting image in X-ray screening.  Upon making the discovery, Customs submitted the package to FedEx Dangerous Goods department for proper reporting.  The shipment was not prepared in accordance with IATA Regulations missing the required markings, labeling, packaging and paperwork.  The shipment is being held, pending an FAA investigation.

column169: BNSF personnel identified a potential release from the TILX 360231 while the car was in the Pasco Bowl Track 43.  The car was isolated pending inspection by BNSF Hazmat personnel.  Upon inspection, gasoline vapor was found emitting from the manway between the nozzle and hinged lid.  The manway was opened and found that the gasket was misaligned and not sealing completely.  The gasket was replaced with a nozzle gasket and the lid secured.  A new seal was installed and the car was released.  There were no identified ground impacts from the release and gasoline spilled on the car had evaporated.  Estimated release volume is based upon responder observations.
column170: The shipper should ensure that proper post loading inspections are conducted to include inspection of the manway gasket to ensure it is sufficient to contain the product while in transportation.(NAR:208)

On Saturday, January 4, 2025, a Occidental Chemical driver made a delivery of Hydrochloric Acid to the Occidental Chemical plant located in Hahnville, LA. The Occidental Chemical driver was loaded at an IMTT facility located in Geismar, LA. While the unloading process was underway, it was discovered that the bleeder valve on the product transfer line that goes to the product storage tank was left open. This resulted in approximately 2,500 gallons of Hydrochloric acid being released from the product line into the containment area. No injuries or exposure to chemical occurred as a result of this event, as well as no off-site impact or environmental impact. The offloading process was halted, bleeder valve closed, containment area drained to sump for processing, and remainder of offload was completed.
column170: The OxyChem truck driver immediately shut down the offloading operation upon discovery. The area was drained to a treatment sump, washed down and cleaned up. Occidental Chemical Taft Plant as well as Occidental Chemical Private Fleet has launched a joint investigation into this incident.

column169: Upon arrival at the destination terminal, this tote was discovered leaking inside the trailer. The tote was immediately turned on it's side to prevent further release. After investigation, it was determined that this tote was damaged due to a load shift during transit. An empty tote was used as dunnage to protect the tote and a piece of wood on the skid broke and was pushed into the tote, causing puncture. The material was a thick liquid and was contained to the trailer floor. The material was absorbed using absorbent material and placed into an overpack container for later disposal.
column170: It is hard to determine the exact cause of this incident because we do not know what the dunnage skid looked like before it was damaged and pushed into the tote. This incident may be used in future dock safety meetings to illustrate the importance of using solid, undamaged skids for dunnage to project freight during transport.

XPO Logistics contacted ERTS regarding crushed boxes with plastic jugs containing hazardous product, Kathon. A contractor dispatched and observed an estimated 2-gallons of product released onto the wooden trailer floor in a 4’x4’ area and the concrete beneath the trailer in a 10’x3’ area as a result of improper blocking and bracing. The contractor neutralized the release using vinegar and containerized two empty jugs last containing product along with absorbents, cardboard, pallet pieces, and PPE. One 55-gallon DF was generated for waste disposal. XPO will manage all waste created from the response. No storm-drains, waterways, or soil were involved in this incident.

Dayton Freight personnel observed approximately two (2) quarts of material released from one (1) 1-gallon metal pails due to improperly loaded freight that resulted in the pails flipping over in the trailer and leaking. The released material impacted the trailer floor. Dayton Freight personnel deployed granular absorbents to the impacted area and gathered the spent material and damaged container and containerized it into two (2) 5-gallon poly drums. Three (3) 5-gallon poly drums were also used to contain three additional jugs of product due to contamination. A total of five (5) 5-gallon poly drums of waste were generated from this spill. The generated waste was staged onsite at the terminal in a secure location. The generated waste will remain onsite for Dayton Freight’s contracted hazardous waste vendor to coordinate disposal.

During the screen process at the SWBA location a fiberboard box containing UN1266 was discovered. The outer fiberboard box did not have any DG markings or paperwork required for transit. The shipmnet is being held at the location.

XPO Logistics terminal BCH experienced a UN3082 Rhonox Herbicide release from a 275-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 165-gallons of product released due to a forklift puncture. The entire trailer floor, a 150’ x 30’ area of the concrete lot below, and 4 drains and 1 catch basin were impacted. All drains lead to the catch basin where the material was contained. The crew utilized a vac truck to remove the product from the catch basin and drains leading to it. Absorbents were deployed to the trailer and concrete lot and worked in. Once the drains were done, absorbent boom was placed in them to collect any residual material. The product remaining the damaged tote was pumped out and the damaged tote was cut up and containerized. Crew returned to site and inspected the drains and flushed and vacuumed them out again. Additional wastewater was generated to be offloaded into totes. Samples were collected to confirm that no residual material remains in the catch basin and samples were collected from the nearby retention pond as well as a precaution. All wastewater was offloaded into totes and all solid cleanup debris was containerized into 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage

As the material was being loaded into a trailer at the destination terminal, a piece of protruding metal from another skid was accidentally pushed into the tote causing damage. The released material was contained to the trailer using neutralizer and absorbent material. The neutralizer and absorbent material was placed into an overpack for proper disposal. The IBC container was also turned on it's side as soon as possible to prevent further release of material.
column170: The forklift operator was counselled and will be recertified on the forklift per company safety policies and procedures. This incident will be used in future dock meeting topics to illustrate the importance of proper forklift operating procedures.

column169: TILX 202010 was found in the Gallup, NM yard with residue around the manway nozzle. Three swing bolts were also found to be loose.
